@DATABASE "pnmscale.guide"
@INDEX "ImageEditor.guide/INDEX"
@FONT helvetica.font 13
@SMARTWRAP

@NODE MAIN "ImageEditor - Operator: Scale [pnmscale]"
@TOC "Operator.guide/MAIN"

@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Scale@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{B}Scale a portable anymap.@{UB}@{LINE}
@{PAR}Reads a portable anymap as input.
Scales it by the specified factor or factors and produces a portable anymap as output.
If the input file is in color, the output will be too, otherwise it will be grayscale.
You can both enlarge and reduce.@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{B}Scale with Aspect Ratio.@{UB}@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 8}
@{PAR}You can use @{B}Scale with @{FG HIGHLIGHT}corresponding@{UB}@{FG TEXT}, with one dimension as a pixel size, and the other dimension will be scaled correspondingly.@{LINE}
@{PAR}You can use @{B}Scale to @{FG HIGHLIGHT}fit in@{UB}@{FG TEXT}, which fits the image into the specified size without changing the aspect ratio.@{LINE}
@{PAR}You can use @{B}Scale @{FG HIGHLIGHT}in %@{UB}@{FG TEXT}, which scales the image to the specified percentage without changing the aspect ratio.@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{B}Scale without Aspect Ratio.@{UB}@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 8}
@{PAR}You can specify different sizes or scales for each axis.@{LINE}
@{PAR}You can specify one dimension as a scale or size, and the other dimension will not be scaled.@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}If you enlarge by a factor of 3 or more, you should probably add a smooth step; otherwise, you can see the original pixels in the resulting image.@{LINE}
@{PAR}See also @{" Enlarge " LINK "pnmenlarge.guide/MAIN"}.@{LINE}
@{PAR}[@{B}pnmscale@{UB}] @{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{I}Copyright (C) 1991 by Jef Poskanzer @{UI}@{FG TEXT}@{LINE}

@ENDNODE
